<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Very similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="marginisepala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea marginisepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in all characteristics and difficult to separate except geographically, although molecular studies suggest the two species are distinct. In the type only, the peduncles are suppressed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species is often confused with and sometimes treated as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Austin 1982a: 38)" baseAuthorityName="Austin" baseAuthorityPageNumber="38" baseAuthorityYear="1982" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aristolochiifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea aristolochiifolia</emphasis>
(Austin 1982a: 38)
</taxonomicName>
but is readily distinguished by the lanceolate to ovate, acute unwarted sepals and by the peduncle which does not pass through the leaf sinus.
</paragraph>
